<!-- ══ OVERVIEW ══ -->
<div class="section active" id="s-overview">
  <h2>The Big Picture</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">An audit is a systematic, independent process of gathering and evaluating evidence about management's financial statement assertions — communicating results via an audit report.</p>

  <h3>System of Investor Protection</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-purple">
      <strong>Management (CEO/CFO)</strong>
      <p>Primarily responsible for fair presentation. SOX §302: must certify F/S are fairly stated, no false/misleading statements, and they've read them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Board / Audit Committee</strong>
      <p>Oversees financial reporting. Audit Committee = independent directors. Oversees internal audit function and external auditor.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-teal">
      <strong>External Auditor</strong>
      <p>Provides opinion on fairness of F/S. Must be independent. For large public companies, also opines on ICFR. Product = the audit report.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold">
      <strong>Internal Auditor</strong>
      <p>Company employees; direct line to Audit Committee. Objective but NOT independent — they work for the company.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-coral">
      <strong>SEC / PCAOB</strong>
      <p>SEC: all issuers must file. PCAOB: oversees public company auditors. &gt;100 issuers = annual inspections; ≤100 = every 3 years.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-orange">
      <strong>Standards</strong>
      <p>PCAOB = public companies. ASB/AICPA = nonpublic. IAASB = international. All CPAs follow AICPA Code of Professional Conduct.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout"><strong>Principal-Agent Problem:</strong> Owners (principals) hire managers (agents) who have an information advantage and may act in self-interest. Auditors provide independent verification to close this gap. In 1926 — before audits were required — 82% of NYSE firms voluntarily paid for audits.</div>

  <h3>Key Definitions</h3>
  <div class="grid3">
    <div class="card"><strong>Assurance</strong><p>Lending credibility by independent/objective intermediaries.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Attestation</strong><p>Assurance for specific assertions made by management.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Auditing</strong><p>Attestation for assertions in financial statements specifically.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h3>GAAS — Three Fundamental Principles</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Responsibilities</div><div class="desc">Competence/capabilities, independence (in fact AND appearance), due care, professional skepticism and judgment.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Performance</div><div class="desc">Proper planning/supervision, assess materiality, assess risk, gather sufficient (quantity) and appropriate (quality) evidence.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Reporting</div><div class="desc">Express an opinion (or state one cannot be expressed) on whether F/S are presented fairly in conformity with GAAP/IFRS.</div></div></div>

  <div class="warn"><strong>Professional Skepticism:</strong> Inquiry alone is NEVER enough. Always obtain corroborative evidence. Ask questions → get answers → verify the answers. "A questioning mindset toward representations made by management."</div>
</div>

<!-- ══ ASSERTIONS ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-assertions">
  <h2>Assertions</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Management's implicit or explicit claims about the financial statements. Every audit procedure maps to one or more assertions. An assertion is <em>relevant</em> only if there's a reasonable possibility it contains a material misstatement.</p>

  <div class="assertion-grid">
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Existence / Occurrence</div><div class="def">Assets/liabilities exist; transactions actually occurred.</div><div class="tip">→ Overstatement risk. Sample from REPORT, vouch back.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Completeness</div><div class="def">All balances and transactions have been recorded.</div><div class="tip">→ Understatement risk. Sample from TRUTH, trace forward.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Valuation / Allocation</div><div class="def">Assets, liabilities, and transactions valued per GAAP.</div><div class="tip">→ Credit ratings of customers = Valuation.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Rights & Obligations</div><div class="def">Entity has legal claim to assets; responsible for liabilities.</div><div class="tip">→ Less commonly tested; often paired with existence.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Presentation & Disclosure</div><div class="def">Accounts in right place; all required disclosures made.</div><div class="tip">→ Tested by reading vs. GAAP requirements.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Cutoff</div><div class="def">Transactions recorded in the correct period.</div><div class="tip">→ Did we ship before year-end? Critical near period end.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Accuracy</div><div class="def">Amounts recorded at correct dollar amounts.</div><div class="tip">→ Tested via recalculation and reperformance.</div></div>
    <div class="a-card"><div class="name">Classification</div><div class="def">Transactions recorded in proper accounts.</div><div class="tip">→ Current vs. noncurrent; revenue vs. gains.</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Vouching vs. Tracing — The Most Tested Concept</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Vouching → Tests Existence</strong>
      <p>Start from the financial report → trace BACK to source documents. "Did this recorded item actually happen?" Sample from sales journal → vouch to invoice, shipping doc, PO.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-teal">
      <strong>Tracing → Tests Completeness</strong>
      <p>Start from source document → follow FORWARD into the report. "Was everything that happened actually recorded?" Sample from shipping docs → trace to sales journal.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Common Assertion Mapping (Exam Favorite)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Assertion</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Credit ratings of customers</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">Valuation</span></td><td>Are receivables valued correctly given creditworthiness?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Goods shipped, not recorded</td><td><span class="badge b-gold">Completeness</span></td><td>Missing transaction — understatement</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sales recorded, goods not shipped</td><td><span class="badge b-red">Existence</span></td><td>Fictitious transaction — overstatement</td></tr>
    <tr><td>January sales in December</td><td><span class="badge b-purple">Cutoff</span></td><td>Wrong period</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Product A recorded as Product B</td><td><span class="badge b-green">Presentation</span></td><td>Wrong account/classification</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sales billed at wrong price</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">Valuation/Accuracy</span></td><td>Wrong dollar amount</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Prenumbered docs accounted for</td><td><span class="badge b-gold">Completeness</span></td><td>Ensures all transactions recorded</td></tr>
    <tr><td>POs require authorization</td><td><span class="badge b-red">Existence</span></td><td>Prevents recording fake POs</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ RISK ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-risk">
  <h2>Audit Risk Model</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">The engine of audit planning. Tells the auditor how much substantive work to perform. Applied at the assertion level.</p>

  <div class="formula">AR = IR × CR × DR</div>

  <div class="grid3">
    <div class="card card-accent-coral">
      <strong>Inherent Risk (IR)</strong>
      <p>Probability of material misstatement before internal controls. Auditor assesses but CANNOT control. Higher for: fair value estimates, complex transactions, fraud-prone accounts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold">
      <strong>Control Risk (CR)</strong>
      <p>Probability that internal controls fail to catch a misstatement. Strong controls → lower CR → less substantive work. Auditor assesses by understanding and testing controls.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Detection Risk (DR)</strong>
      <p>The ONLY risk the auditor directly controls. Probability that substantive procedures miss a misstatement. DR = AR ÷ (IR × CR).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout"><strong>Key insight:</strong> High IR + High CR → must set DR LOW → need MORE substantive work (more tests, larger samples, year-end testing, more effective procedures).</div>

  <h3>Interactive Risk Calculator</h3>
  <div class="calc-box">
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Audit Risk Target</label>
      <select id="ar-val" onchange="calcRisk()">
        <option value="0.05">5% — typical</option>
        <option value="0.10">10% — lower risk client</option>
        <option value="0.01">1% — very strict</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Inherent Risk</label>
      <select id="ir-val" onchange="calcRisk()">
        <option value="1.0">High (1.0)</option>
        <option value="0.5">Moderate (0.5)</option>
        <option value="0.25">Low (0.25)</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Control Risk</label>
      <select id="cr-val" onchange="calcRisk()">
        <option value="1.0">Max / High (1.0)</option>
        <option value="0.5">Moderate (0.5)</option>
        <option value="0.25">Low (0.25)</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div id="risk-result" class="calc-result"></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Effect on Substantive Procedures</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th></th><th>Lower DR needed (more work)</th><th>Higher DR ok (less work)</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Nature</strong></td><td>More effective tests (confirmation, physical inspection)</td><td>Less effective tests (inquiry, analytics)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Timing</strong></td><td>More testing at year-end</td><td>More testing at interim</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Extent</strong></td><td>Larger samples, more tests</td><td>Smaller samples, fewer tests</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Fraud Triangle</h3>
  <div class="grid3">
    <div class="card card-accent-coral"><strong>Incentive / Pressure</strong><p>Financial pressures, analyst expectations, personal financial situation, bonus tied to results</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Opportunity</strong><p>Weak internal controls, complex organizational structure, override ability</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-orange"><strong>Rationalization</strong><p>Management's belief the ends justify the means; history of securities violations</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="danger"><strong>Fraud vs. Error:</strong> The difference is intent. Any management fraud is considered material and must be reported to the audit committee. Must communicate fraud up at least one level above the persons involved.</div>
</div>

<!-- ══ MATERIALITY ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-materiality">
  <h2>Materiality</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">A fact is material if "a reasonable investor would view it as having significantly altered the total mix of information available." Focus is on the user — not management, not the auditor.</p>

  <h3>Three-Step Process</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Overall (Planning) Materiality</div><div class="desc">5% of income before taxes is the most common benchmark for public companies. May be lowered for: prior misstatements, high fraud risk, loan covenant pressure, volatile industry.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Tolerable Misstatement (Performance Materiality)</div><div class="desc">Allocated to individual accounts. Typically 50–75% of overall materiality. Used to design tests for each account.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Evaluate Audit Findings</div><div class="desc">Aggregate known + likely misstatements. If aggregate &lt; overall materiality AND no account exceeds tolerable misstatement → quantitatively fairly presented. Don't forget qualitative factors.</div></div></div>

  <h3>Interactive Materiality Calculator</h3>
  <div class="calc-box">
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Income Before Taxes ($)</label><input type="number" id="ibt" value="1000000000" onchange="calcMat()"></div>
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Overall Materiality % (e.g. 5)</label><input type="number" id="om-pct" value="5" min="1" max="15" step="0.5" onchange="calcMat()"></div>
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Tolerable % of OM (e.g. 50)</label><input type="number" id="tm-pct" value="50" min="25" max="75" step="5" onchange="calcMat()"></div>
    <div class="calc-row"><label>Clearly Trivial % of OM (e.g. 3)</label><input type="number" id="ct-pct" value="3" min="1" max="5" step="0.5" onchange="calcMat()"></div>
    <div id="mat-result" class="calc-result"></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Qualitative Factors</h3>
  <ul style="margin-top:6px;padding-left:1.2rem;font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);">
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Does the misstatement change a loss into income (or vice versa)?</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Will it increase management's compensation?</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Effect on compliance with loan covenants</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Effect on profitability trends</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout" style="margin-top:12px;"><strong>Clearly Trivial:</strong> 3–5% of overall materiality. Don't even need to tell the client. Everything else must be accumulated and communicated to the audit committee (even if not adjusted).</div>
</div>

<!-- ══ EVIDENCE ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-evidence">
  <h2>Audit Evidence</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Evidence must be sufficient (enough quantity) and appropriate (high quality = relevant + reliable). Higher quality evidence means you need less of it.</p>

  <h3>Reliability Hierarchy</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num" style="background:rgba(105,219,124,.2);color:var(--green);">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Auditor's direct knowledge</div><div class="desc">Physical inspection, observation, reperformance — you did it yourself. Most reliable.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num" style="background:rgba(116,192,252,.2);color:var(--blue);">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Independent external sources</div><div class="desc">Bank statements from bank, confirmations from customers, published data. Reliable because source has no stake in management's assertions.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num" style="background:rgba(255,169,77,.2);color:var(--orange);">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Internal documents (strong controls)</div><div class="desc">Reasonably reliable when controls are effective.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num" style="background:rgba(255,107,107,.2);color:var(--coral);">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Inquiry of management</div><div class="desc">Least reliable — always needs corroboration. Inquiry ALONE is never sufficient.</div></div></div>

  <h3>Types of Audit Procedures</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>Inspection of Records</strong><p>Vouching (existence), Tracing (completeness), Scanning (looking for anomalies)</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Inspection of Tangible Assets</strong><p>Physical verification. Tests existence — "kick the tires."</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Observation</strong><p>Watching a procedure performed. Only valid at that moment in time.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Inquiry</strong><p>Asking questions. Weakest form. Never sufficient alone.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Confirmation</strong><p>Info directly from third parties. Strong for existence. (Bank, customer AR)</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Recalculation</strong><p>Redoing the client's math. Tests accuracy/valuation.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Reperformance</strong><p>Independently executing a procedure the client performed.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Analytical Procedures</strong><p>Evaluating relationships among data. Required in planning and final review. Optional as substantive test.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Confirmations</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Positive Confirmations</strong>
      <p>Ask: "Is this balance correct?" Requires a response. Use when: few accounts, high expected errors, large balances. Blank confirmations are best when recipient might just confirm without actually checking.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-teal">
      <strong>Negative Confirmations</strong>
      <p>Respond ONLY if something is wrong. Use only when: low RMM, large number of small balances, customers expected to respond carefully. Non-response ≠ evidence of correctness.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="warn">Recipients might not report understatements. Be skeptical of responses via unusual channels. Non-response to a positive confirmation always requires follow-up or alternative procedures.</div>

  <h3>Analytical Procedure Steps</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Develop an independent expectation</div><div class="desc">Use reliable, independent data sources</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Define a tolerable difference</div><div class="desc">How much variance before you investigate?</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Compare expectation to recorded amount</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Investigate significant differences</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Document all steps</div></div></div>

  <h3>Documentation Requirements</h3>
  <ul style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);padding-left:1.2rem;margin-top:6px;">
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Enable experienced auditor with no prior connection to understand nature, timing, extent, results, conclusions</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Who did it, when, who reviewed, when reviewed</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Finalized within <strong style="color:var(--text);">45 days</strong> of audit report release date</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Retained for <strong style="color:var(--text);">7 years</strong> from report release date</li>
    <li>Must include listing of significant accounts and relevant assertions</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- ══ ICFR ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-icfr">
  <h2>Internal Controls & SOX</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Management is responsible for maintaining effective internal controls. Auditors must gain an understanding of controls related to financial reporting.</p>

  <h3>COSO Framework — 5 Components</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Control Environment</div><div class="desc">"Tone at the top." The foundation for all other components. Board independence, ethical values, accountability. Auditor must document a detailed understanding.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Risk Assessment</div><div class="desc">Management's identification and analysis of risks (including fraud risk). This is management's process — NOT the auditor's risk assessment.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Control Activities</div><div class="desc">Policies and procedures: segregation of duties, authorization requirements, prenumbered docs, reconciliations, restricted physical access.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Information & Communication</div><div class="desc">Controls over quality of information and how it's communicated internally and externally. Auditors cannot blindly rely on company information systems.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Monitoring</div><div class="desc">Periodic evaluations by internal audit, supervisory review, audit committee inquiries. "Controls over controls."</div></div></div>

  <h3>SOX Requirements</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-gold">
      <strong>Section 404a — All Issuers</strong>
      <p>Management must report its own tests of ICFR in the annual 10-K. Management accepts responsibility, evaluates effectiveness, supports with documentation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Section 404b — Accelerated Filers Only</strong>
      <p>External auditor independently assesses ICFR. Results in an integrated audit (opinion on F/S + opinion on ICFR). Applies to companies with market cap &gt;$75M.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout"><strong>Filing deadlines:</strong> &gt;$700M market cap = Large Accelerated (60 days). $75M–$700M = Accelerated (75 days). &lt;$75M = Non-Accelerated (90 days, no 404b required).</div>

  <h3>Deficiency Severity Table</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Deficiency Type</th><th>Report to Mgmt?</th><th>Report to Audit Cmte?</th><th>Adverse ICFR Opinion?</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Any deficiency</td><td><span class="badge b-green">✓ Yes</span></td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Significant deficiency</td><td><span class="badge b-green">✓ Yes</span></td><td><span class="badge b-green">✓ Yes</span></td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Material weakness</td><td><span class="badge b-green">✓ Yes</span></td><td><span class="badge b-green">✓ Yes</span></td><td><span class="badge b-red">✓ Adverse</span></td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>
  <div class="danger"><strong>Material Weakness:</strong> A reasonable possibility that a material misstatement will NOT be prevented or detected on a timely basis. Even ONE material weakness requires an adverse ICFR opinion. There is no "qualified" ICFR opinion — only unqualified or adverse.</div>

  <h3>Audit Strategies for Controls</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-coral">
      <strong>Substantive Strategy</strong>
      <p>Set CR at HIGH. Use when: controls don't pertain to an assertion, controls are likely ineffective, or testing controls is inefficient. Then perform MORE substantive work.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-green">
      <strong>Reliance Strategy</strong>
      <p>Test controls to validate design and operating effectiveness. If controls pass → CR is LOW → DR can be HIGH → LESS substantive work needed.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>SOC Reports</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>SOC 1 Type 1</strong><p>Covers the design of ICFR at a service organization (e.g., ADP) relevant to user entity's ICFR.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>SOC 1 Type 2</strong><p>Covers design AND effectiveness of controls. More comprehensive — includes testing over a period.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ SAMPLING ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-sampling">
  <h2>Audit Sampling</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Selecting less than 100% of a population to draw conclusions about the whole. Statistical sampling uses probability laws; nonstatistical does not.</p>

  <h3>The Two Sampling Errors</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-gold">
      <strong>Type I — Incorrect Rejection / Underreliance</strong>
      <p>Sample says "problem exists." Reality: it doesn't. → <em>Efficiency</em> loss — you do extra unnecessary work. Not dangerous; just wastes time and money.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-coral">
      <strong>Type II — Incorrect Acceptance / Overreliance</strong>
      <p>Sample says "everything is fine." Reality: there IS a problem. → <em>Effectiveness</em> loss — you miss a real error and may issue a wrong opinion. Dangerous!</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Attribute Sampling — Tests of Controls</h3>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin:8px 0 12px;">Used to estimate the <em>rate of deviation</em> in a control. Compare ULRD to TRD.</p>
  <div class="formula">ULRD = Sample Deviation Rate + Allowance for Sampling Risk</div>
  <div class="grid2" style="margin-top:8px;">
    <div class="card card-accent-green"><strong>ULRD ≤ TRD</strong><p>Rely on controls as planned. Maintain planned CR and DR.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-coral"><strong>ULRD &gt; TRD</strong><p>Reduce reliance on controls. Increase CR → need more substantive work.</p></div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:12px;color:var(--text2);margin-top:8px;">Steps: (1) Select sample size table for desired risk of overreliance → use EPDR and TRD. (2) Perform tests, count deviations. (3) Find ULRD using evaluation table (sample size × # of deviations). (4) Compare ULRD to TRD.</p>

  <h3>Variables Sampling — Substantive Tests</h3>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin:8px 0 12px;">Used to estimate the <em>dollar amount of misstatement</em>. Compare ULM to TM (Tolerable Misstatement).</p>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-green"><strong>ULM ≤ TM</strong><p>Account balance is not materially misstated — accept it.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-coral"><strong>ULM &gt; TM</strong><p>Account balance is misstated — investigate, request adjustments, or modify opinion.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Factors Affecting Sample Size</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Effect</th><th>Logic</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Population size</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">↑ Direct (small)</span></td><td>Larger pop → slightly more sampling needed</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Expected rate of deviation / misstatement</td><td><span class="badge b-red">↑ Direct</span></td><td>More errors expected → need more evidence</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Tolerable rate / misstatement</td><td><span class="badge b-green">↓ Inverse</span></td><td>More tolerance → less precision needed</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Desired sampling risk</td><td><span class="badge b-red">↑ (more sample)</span></td><td>Lower risk = larger sample needed</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Population variability</td><td><span class="badge b-red">↑ Direct</span></td><td>More variation → less representative small sample</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>

  
  <h3>Nonstatistical Sampling Policy (Typical Firm)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <tr><th>Risk Level</th><th>Sample Size Range</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Low</td><td>10–20 items</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderate</td><td>20–33 items</td></tr>
    <tr><td>High</td><td>30–48 items</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="callout">With nonstatistical sampling, you CAN calculate a sample deviation rate, but you CANNOT mathematically quantify the upper limit rate of deviation or sampling risk. The conclusion relies on auditor judgment rather than probability tables.</div>

  <h3>Nonstatistical Sampling Policy (Typical Firm)</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <tr><th>Risk Level</th><th>Sample Size Range</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Low</td><td>10&ndash;20 items</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderate</td><td>20&ndash;33 items</td></tr>
    <tr><td>High</td><td>30&ndash;48 items</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="callout">With nonstatistical sampling, you CAN calculate a sample deviation rate, but CANNOT mathematically quantify the upper limit rate of deviation. The conclusion relies on auditor judgment rather than probability tables.</div>

<h3>Sample Selection Methods</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>Unrestricted Random</strong><p>Random numbers matched to items. ✓ Can use with statistical sampling.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Systematic Random</strong><p>Every nth item after a random start. ✓ Can use with statistical sampling.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Block Selection</strong><p>Contiguous items (e.g., all December transactions). ✗ Cannot use with statistical sampling.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Haphazard</strong><p>No pattern — humans trying to be random. ✗ Cannot use with statistical sampling.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ CYCLES ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-cycles">
  <h2>Cash & Revenue Cycles</h2>
  <div class="tab-row">
    <button class="tab-btn on" onclick="showTab('cash-tab','cy')">Cash</button>
    <button class="tab-btn" onclick="showTab('rev-tab','cy')">Revenue & AR</button>
  </div>

  <div class="sub-section on" id="cash-tab">
    <h3>Cash: Relevant Assertions</h3>
    <div class="grid3">
      <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>Existence</strong><p>Cash balance actually exists in bank accounts.</p></div>
      <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Valuation</strong><p>Foreign currency translation is correct.</p></div>
      <div class="card card-accent-teal"><strong>Presentation</strong><p>Properly classified and disclosed.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout">Cash is liquid, easily transportable, and used to pay debts. Inherently risky. Completeness is less of a concern — you'd notice if cash disappeared.</div>

    <h3>Bank Reconciliation Audit Steps</h3>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Rec Item</th><th>Audit Procedure</th><th>Assertion</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Balance per bank</td><td>Confirm directly with bank (standard bank confirmation)</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">Existence</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Deposits in transit</td><td>Vouch to cutoff bank statement; trace from cash receipts journal</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">Existence</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Outstanding checks</td><td>Trace to cutoff bank statement; vouch to cash disbursements journal</td><td><span class="badge b-gold">Completeness</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bank debit/credit memos</td><td>Inspect bank memo and supporting docs for reasonableness</td><td><span class="badge b-purple">Valuation</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Balance per books</td><td>Foot the reconciliation; trace to trial balance</td><td><span class="badge b-blue">Accuracy</span></td></tr>
    </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Cash Disbursements — Internal Control</h3>
    <div class="card">
      <p>Voucher packet (Purchase Requisition + PO + Receiving Report + Invoice) must be matched and marked PAID before payment. The person recording the AP entry should NOT have check-writing access — classic segregation of duties.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="danger"><strong>Incompatible function for cashier:</strong> If the cashier receives remittances, they should NOT also post to the AR subsidiary ledger. This combination allows them to steal cash and cover it up by not recording the receipt.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="sub-section" id="rev-tab">
    <h3>Revenue & AR: Relevant Assertions</h3>
    <div class="grid2">
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Revenue</strong>
        <ul style="margin-top:4px;"><li>Occurrence</li><li>Completeness</li><li>Cutoff</li></ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>Accounts Receivable</strong>
        <ul style="margin-top:4px;"><li>Existence</li><li>Completeness</li><li>Valuation (collectability)</li></ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Assertion → Test Mapping</h3>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Assertion</th><th>What Could Go Wrong</th><th>Substantive Test</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Occurrence/Existence</td><td>Fictitious sales/AR (inflating revenue)</td><td>Sample from sales journal → vouch to shipping docs, invoice, PO</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Completeness</td><td>Not all sales recorded</td><td>Sample from shipping docs → trace to sales journal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Valuation (AR)</td><td>Uncollectible AR not estimated properly</td><td>Inspect aging schedule; inquire of credit manager; recompute allowance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cutoff</td><td>Recording in wrong period</td><td>Test shipments near year-end; compare shipping dates to recording dates</td></tr>
    </table>
    </div>

    <h3>AR Confirmations</h3>
    <div class="grid2">
      <div class="card card-accent-blue">
        <strong>Positive (and Blank)</strong>
        <p>Large balances, high error expected, few accounts. Blank form is preferred when recipient might confirm without checking. Non-response must be followed up.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card card-accent-teal">
        <strong>Negative</strong>
        <p>Use only when: low RMM, large number of small balances, customers expected to respond. Non-response ≠ confirmation. Respond only if something is wrong.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="warn">Recipients tend not to report understatements. Be skeptical of responses via unusual channels (fax, email). Always follow up on exceptions.</div>

    <h3>Alternative Procedures (When No Confirmation Response)</h3>
    <ul style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);padding-left:1.2rem;margin-top:6px;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Vouch to subsequent cash collections — best alternative</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Inspect shipping documents (Bill of Lading — third-party evidence)</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Inspect sales orders, invoices, and other supporting docs</li>
      <li>Inspect correspondence files for past-due accounts</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ REPORTING ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-reporting">
  <h2>Audit Opinions & Reports</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">The audit report is your product. Understand every opinion type and when each is required.</p>

  <h3>Types of Opinions</h3>
  <div class="op-card op-green"><div class="op-title">Unmodified / Unqualified (Clean)</div><div class="op-desc">F/S are fairly presented in conformity with GAAP. No issues. The normal outcome.</div></div>
  <div class="op-card op-blue"><div class="op-title">Unmodified + Explanatory Paragraphs</div><div class="op-desc">F/S are fine, but additional items must be disclosed: going concern, ICFR reference, CAMs, consistency changes. Still a "clean" opinion.</div></div>
  <div class="op-card op-gold"><div class="op-title">Qualified ("Except For")</div><div class="op-desc">Except for one material (but not pervasive) issue, F/S are fairly stated. Used for GAAP departure OR scope limitation that is material but not pervasive.</div></div>
  <div class="op-card op-red"><div class="op-title">Adverse</div><div class="op-desc">F/S are NOT fairly stated. GAAP departure that is BOTH material AND pervasive. The worst opinion.</div></div>
  <div class="op-card op-gray"><div class="op-title">Disclaimer</div><div class="op-desc">Auditor does NOT express an opinion. Scope limitation so severe no conclusion can be formed. Also used in extremely serious going concern situations.</div></div>

  <h3>Decision Trees</h3>
  <div class="tab-row">
    <button class="tab-btn on" onclick="showTab('gaap-tab','rt')">GAAP Departure</button>
    <button class="tab-btn" onclick="showTab('scope-tab','rt')">Scope Limitation</button>
  </div>
  <div class="sub-section on" id="gaap-tab">
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Material?</th><th>Pervasive?</th><th>Opinion</th></tr>
      <tr><td>No</td><td>—</td><td><span class="badge b-green">Clean</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td><span class="badge b-gold">Qualified</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td><td><span class="badge b-red">Adverse</span></td></tr>
    </table>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="sub-section" id="scope-tab">
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Material?</th><th>Pervasive?</th><th>Alt Procedures?</th><th>Opinion</th></tr>
      <tr><td>No</td><td>—</td><td>—</td><td><span class="badge b-green">Clean</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yes</td><td>—</td><td>Yes → resolved</td><td><span class="badge b-green">Clean</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td>No</td><td><span class="badge b-gold">Qualified</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td><span class="badge b-red">Disclaimer</span></td></tr>
    </table>
    </div>
    <div class="warn" style="margin-top:8px;">Client-imposed scope limitations are almost always considered pervasive → Disclaimer. Circumstance-imposed limitations (natural disaster, late appointment) may allow qualified opinion.</div>
  </div>

  <h3>Explanatory Paragraphs (Clean but with Notes)</h3>
  <ul style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);padding-left:1.2rem;margin-top:6px;">
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Going concern:</strong> Substantial doubt about ability to continue — add explanatory paragraph (still unmodified). If NOT disclosed by management → qualified or adverse.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Consistency:</strong> Change in accounting principle (e.g., LIFO to FIFO) — explanatory paragraph. If change not justified → qualified.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">CAMs:</strong> Required for large accelerated filers. Matters communicated to audit committee involving especially challenging/complex/subjective judgment. PCAOB only — not for private companies.</li>
    <li><strong style="color:var(--text);">ICFR reference:</strong> For integrated audits, reference the other opinion.</li>
  </ul>

  
  <h3>Group Financial Statements &amp; Component Auditors</h3>
  <div class="callout">Group F/S = F/S comprised of more than one division, subsidiary, or component. Group auditors conduct the primary audit. Component auditors may audit subsidiaries.</div>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <tr><th>Decision</th><th>Result</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor takes responsibility for component work</td><td>Standard unmodified opinion — no reference to component auditor</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor does NOT take responsibility; names component auditor (with their permission)</td><td>Indicate division of responsibility in unmodified opinion; present component auditor report</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor refers to component auditor's work</td><td>Indicate division of responsibility in unmodified opinion</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="card">Group auditors should: (1) verify component auditors' reputation and independence, (2) communicate and coordinate throughout the engagement.</div>

  <h3>Comparative Financial Statements</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>Continuing Auditors</strong><p>Update prior opinion by considering if it's still appropriate. Must be clear which opinion applies to which year.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Predecessor Auditors</strong><p>May reissue their prior report. If not reissued, current auditor's report must reference the predecessor's opinion and date on prior-year F/S.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Other Information in Documents Containing Audited F/S</h3>
  <div class="card">Auditor is REQUIRED to READ other information (e.g., MD&amp;A, president's letter) in annual reports. Must consider whether it's consistent with the audited F/S. The auditor has NO obligation to perform audit procedures OVER the other information — just read and flag material inconsistencies.</div>

  <h3>Can a Company Receive Clean F/S Opinion + Adverse ICFR Opinion?</h3>
  <div class="success"><strong>YES.</strong> A material weakness means there is a RISK that a material misstatement could go undetected — it does not mean a misstatement actually exists in the F/S. If no actual material misstatement is found, the F/S opinion can still be clean. See Peloton's June 30, 2022 10-K as a real example. This is a favorite exam question.</div>

  <h3>Group Financial Statements &amp; Component Auditors</h3>
  <div class="callout">Group F/S = F/S of more than one division, subsidiary, or component. Group auditors conduct the primary audit. Component auditors may audit subsidiaries.</div>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <tr><th>Decision</th><th>Result in Report</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor takes responsibility for component work</td><td>Standard unmodified opinion &mdash; no reference to component auditor</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor does NOT take responsibility; names component auditor (with their permission)</td><td>Present component auditor report; indicate division of responsibility</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Group auditor refers to component auditor's work without naming</td><td>Indicate division of responsibility in unmodified opinion</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="card">Group auditors must: (1) verify component auditors' reputation and independence, (2) communicate and coordinate throughout the engagement.</div>

  <h3>Comparative Financial Statements</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>Continuing Auditors</strong><p>Update prior opinion by considering if it's still appropriate. Must be clear which opinion applies to which year.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Predecessor Auditors</strong><p>May reissue their prior report. If NOT reissued, current auditor's report must reference the predecessor's opinion and date on prior-year F/S.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Other Information in Documents Containing Audited F/S</h3>
  <div class="card">Auditor is REQUIRED to READ other information (MD&amp;A, president's letter, etc.) in annual reports. Must consider whether it's consistent with the audited F/S. The auditor has NO obligation to perform audit procedures OVER this other information &mdash; just read it and flag material inconsistencies.</div>

  <h3>Can a Company Have a Clean F/S Opinion + Adverse ICFR Opinion?</h3>
  <div class="success"><strong>YES.</strong> A material weakness means there is a RISK that a material misstatement could go undetected &mdash; not that a misstatement actually exists. If no actual material misstatement is found, the F/S opinion can still be clean. See Peloton's June 30, 2022 10-K as a real-world example. This is a favorite exam question.</div>

<h3>Subsequent Events</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>Type I — Adjust F/S</strong><p>Evidence of conditions that existed at the balance sheet date. Settlement of a lawsuit where liability already existed at year-end. Must adjust the financial statements.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Type II — Disclose Only</strong><p>New conditions that did NOT exist at year-end. New lawsuit filed after, natural disaster, stock issuance. Require disclosure and possibly pro forma statements.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══ ETHICS ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-ethics">
  <h2>Ethics & Independence</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">The AICPA Code of Professional Conduct applies to ALL CPAs. The SEC requires signing auditors to be CPAs — and courts hold them to the AICPA Code.</p>

  <h3>AICPA Code Structure</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Principles (Aspirational)</div><div class="desc">Responsibilities, Public Interest, Integrity, Objectivity & Independence, Due Care, Scope of Services</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Rules of Conduct (Minimum Standards)</div><div class="desc">Specific enforceable rules</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Interpretations</div><div class="desc">Guidance on how to apply the rules</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Ethical Rulings</div><div class="desc">Published Q&As on specific situations</div></div></div>

  <h3>Independence Threats (Rule 1.200)</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>Familiarity</strong><p>Long or close relationship with client</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Self-Review</strong><p>Reviewing your own work (e.g., did the bookkeeping AND the audit)</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Adverse Interest</strong><p>Suing each other (threatened litigation impairs independence)</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Undue Influence</strong><p>Client threatens to replace auditor over a disagreement</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Financial Self-Interest</strong><p>Owning stock in the client</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Management Participation</strong><p>Acting in a management role for the client</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Advocacy</strong><p>Promoting the client's interests (e.g., expert witness in their favor)</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout"><strong>Rule 1.100 — Integrity and Objectivity:</strong> "If it seems bad, it is bad." You can violate this even without technically breaking Rule 1.200. Don't subordinate your judgment to others.</div>

  <h3>Covered Members & Restrictions</h3>
  <div class="callout">Covered members = anyone on the engagement + anyone who can influence it + partner in the same office + firm's benefit plans + entities controlled by covered members.</div>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Person</th><th>Restriction</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Covered member / spouse / dependents</td><td>Cannot have any direct financial interest; no material indirect interest; no loans to/from client</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Close relatives (parents, siblings, non-dependent children)</td><td>Cannot be in management position at client; cannot have material interest known to covered member</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Audit partners</td><td>Limited to 5 consecutive years; 1-year "cooling off" period before financial oversight role at former client</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Key Rules Quick Reference</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Rule</th><th>Topic</th><th>Key Points</th></tr>
    <tr><td>1.200</td><td>Independence</td><td>All independence threats. 3rd-party lawsuits don't impair; mutual lawsuits do.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.100</td><td>Integrity/Objectivity</td><td>No conflicts of interest; don't subordinate judgment</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.400</td><td>Acts Discreditable</td><td>False JEs, failure to file taxes, cheating on CPA exam</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.500</td><td>Fees</td><td>Contingent fees NOT allowed for attest clients. Commissions NOT allowed for attest clients. Flat referral fees always OK if disclosed.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.600</td><td>Advertising</td><td>Allowed, but not false/misleading. Can't underquote fees or claim ability to influence third parties.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.700</td><td>Confidentiality</td><td>No disclosure without consent — except court subpoena, PCAOB/peer review, ethics investigation</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1.800</td><td>Firm Name</td><td>Can't be misleading; all partners in firm name must be CPAs</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>
  <div class="warn"><strong>SEC additions:</strong> Partners limited to 5 years on public clients. Firm isn't independent if partner compensation is based on selling non-audit services to the audit client. Tax services for key executives impair independence.</div>
</div>

<!-- ══ COMPLETION ══ -->
<div class="section" id="s-completion">
  <h2>Completing the Audit</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">The final stretch — from year-end procedures through report issuance and beyond.</p>

  <h3>Audit Timeline</h3>
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-dot"></div>
      <div class="tl-title">Interim Period</div>
      <div class="tl-desc">Tests of controls + some substantive procedures. Must "roll forward" to year-end later.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-dot"></div>
      <div class="tl-title">Balance Sheet Date (Year-End)</div>
      <div class="tl-desc">Complete substantive procedures. Subsequent events search begins here.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item highlight">
      <div class="tl-dot"></div>
      <div class="tl-title">Audit Completion Date (Report Date)</div>
      <div class="tl-desc">Rep letters dated here. Attorney's letters completed. Going-concern assessment done. Subsequent events search ends here. Audit documentation review.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-dot"></div>
      <div class="tl-title">Audit Report Release Date</div>
      <div class="tl-desc">Report issued to public. 45-day clock starts for documentation finalization. 7-year retention period starts.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-dot"></div>
      <div class="tl-title">After Release — Subsequently Discovered Facts</div>
      <div class="tl-desc">Facts discovered after the report date that may require revision or notification to those relying on the F/S.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Attorney's Letters</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Auditor initiates the request</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Client prepares a listing of all litigation, claims, and assessments</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Auditor sends it to the attorney</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Attorney responds — confirming or modifying the client's description</div></div></div>

  <h3>Written Representations (Rep Letter)</h3>
  <ul style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);padding-left:1.2rem;margin-top:6px;">
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Provided by management, dated as of the audit report date</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Purpose: management acknowledges primary responsibility for F/S; establishes auditor's defense</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:4px;">Think of it as "hand on the Bible"</li>
    <li>If not provided: typically disclaim or qualify the opinion</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Going Concern</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-green"><strong>Concerns Resolved</strong><p>Management's plans adequately address the concern → no effect on report.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Concerns Remain</strong><p>Add explanatory paragraph to the unmodified opinion. If extremely serious → disclaimer (rare).</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="danger">If management does NOT properly disclose going concern uncertainty → that's a GAAP departure → qualified or adverse opinion.</div>

  <h3>Subsequent Events vs. Subsequently Discovered Facts</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-blue">
      <strong>Subsequent Events</strong>
      <p>Occur between balance sheet date and audit report date. Type I = adjust F/S (condition existed). Type II = disclose only (new condition).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-accent-purple">
      <strong>Subsequently Discovered Facts</strong>
      <p>Discovered AFTER report date. If before release → revise or dual-date. If after release → notify those relying on F/S.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

