<!-- CH2 STANDARDS -->
<div class="section" id="s-standards">
  <h2>Chapter 2 &#8212; Standards, Regulation &amp; Quality</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Who sets the rules, who enforces them, and how audit firms maintain quality internally.</p>
  <h3>Expectations Gap</h3>
  <div class="warn">Many users believe auditors should detect ALL misstatements. In reality, the auditor obtains reasonable assurance that F/S are free of <strong>material</strong> misstatement. Management has ultimate responsibility. CEOs/CFOs must certify F/S under SOX &#167;302.</div>
  <h3>Who Sets Auditing Standards?</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <tr><th>Body</th><th>Applies To</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>PCAOB</strong></td><td>Public companies (issuers)</td><td>Created by SOX 2002. Quasi-private. SEC oversees PCAOB.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>ASB (AICPA)</strong></td><td>Nonpublic companies</td><td>Issues Statements on Auditing Standards</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>IAASB</strong></td><td>&gt;100 countries internationally</td><td>Issues International Standards on Auditing</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="callout">Even for public companies, the signing auditor must be a CPA, and courts hold CPAs to the AICPA Code of Professional Conduct. So AICPA rules apply to all auditors.</div>
  <h3>Regulation of Audit Firms</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>AICPA Peer Review (Nonpublic)</strong><p>One firm reviews another firm's practice. Self-regulatory. For firms auditing nonpublic entities only.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>PCAOB Inspections (Public)</strong><p>Annual for firms auditing &gt;100 issuers. Every 3 years for &le;100 issuers. Part I = individual engagement deficiencies. Part II = quality control system deficiencies.</p></div>
  </div>
  <h3>System of Quality Control &#8212; 6 Elements</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Leadership responsibilities ("Tone at the top")</div><div class="desc">Partner compensation and advancement tied to audit quality</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Relevant ethical requirements</div><div class="desc">Independence, integrity, objectivity</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Acceptance and continuance of client relationships</div><div class="desc">Two-way process &#8212; firm evaluates client AND client evaluates firm</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Human resources</div><div class="desc">Hiring, training, assignment of personnel</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Engagement performance</div><div class="desc">Consultation, supervision, review</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">6</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Monitoring</div><div class="desc">Ongoing evaluation of quality control policies</div></div></div>
  <h3>Prohibited Non-Audit Services for Audit Clients (SOX / PCAOB)</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><ul><li>Bookkeeping</li><li>Financial info systems design / implementation</li><li>Appraisal or valuation services</li><li>Actuarial services</li><li>Internal audit outsourcing</li></ul></div>
    <div class="card"><ul><li>Management functions</li><li>Human resources</li><li>Broker-dealer services</li><li>Legal services</li><li>Any service for a contingent fee</li><li>Tax services for key executives</li></ul></div>
  </div>
  <div class="purple-box"><strong>Private equity trend (2022&#8211;2023):</strong> Grant Thornton (New Mountain Capital), Baker Tilly (Hellman &amp; Friedman), EisnerAmper and others received PE investment. Grant Thornton is now the largest audit firm that is no longer a strict partnership. Raises questions about independence and quality.</div>
</div>

<!-- CH3 PRE-ENGAGEMENT -->
<div class="section" id="s-preengagement">
  <h2>Chapter 3 &#8212; Pre-Engagement &amp; Audit Planning</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Everything that happens before substantive testing begins &#8212; client acceptance, planning, staffing, and understanding the client.</p>
  <h3>Pre-Engagement Activities (4 Steps)</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Client Acceptance or Continuance</div><div class="desc">Two-way process. Firm evaluates client (integrity, competence, independence). Client evaluates firm. Either party can walk away.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Communication with Predecessor Auditors</div><div class="desc">Attempt to communicate is REQUIRED. If client permits, discuss: management integrity issues, disagreements on accounting or audit procedures, fraud / illegal acts communication, reason for auditor change. The client must allow the predecessor to respond to the successor's inquiries.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Independence and Ethical Compliance</div><div class="desc">Independence in fact (mental state) AND in appearance (perception of a reasonable investor). Lack of independence can result in disciplinary action and litigation.</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Engagement Letter</div><div class="desc">Formal contract outlining responsibilities of both client and auditor (AS 1301 / AU-C 210). Protects both parties. Covers scope, fees, and responsibilities.</div></div></div>
  <h3>Staffing the Engagement</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>Typical Team</strong><ul><li>Audit engagement partner</li><li>Audit manager</li><li>Senior associates and associates</li><li>IT audit specialist</li><li>Tax partner</li><li>Quality assurance (reviewing) partner</li></ul></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Assignment Rule</strong><p>More experienced staff assigned to: new clients, complex transactions, and public clients. The quality assurance (reviewing) partner checks in on the engagement but is not the day-to-day leader.</p></div>
  </div>
  <h3>Using Internal Auditors</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-teal"><strong>Reliance</strong><p>External auditor relies on work already performed by internal auditors. Must assess their objectivity and competence first. Rely LESS (or not at all) in high-risk or highly judgmental areas. Should not delegate tasks requiring extensive professional judgment.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-blue"><strong>Direct Assistance</strong><p>Internal auditors join the external audit team directly. By definition, internal auditors are NOT independent (they work for the company) but can be objective.</p></div>
  </div>
  <h3>Specialists</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card card-accent-gold"><strong>Auditor-Employed Specialists</strong><p>Hired by the audit firm (actuaries, geologists, appraisers). Must know their qualifications and reputation. Should be unrelated to the client. Typically NOT referred to in the audit report.</p></div>
    <div class="card card-accent-orange"><strong>Company-Employed Specialists</strong><p>Works for the client. Must consider their objectivity and competence. Extent of evaluation depends on: RMM in the area, significance of work, and specialist's objectivity and competence.</p></div>
  </div>
  <h3>Interim vs. Year-End Work</h3>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><strong>Interim Audit Work</strong><p>Performed weeks or months BEFORE the balance sheet date. Tests of controls and some substantive procedures. Must be rolled forward to year-end.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Year-End Audit Work</strong><p>Performed shortly before AND after the balance sheet date. Complete substantive procedures, attorney letters, rep letters, going-concern assessment.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- CH4 INHERENT RISK -->
<div class="section" id="s-inherent">
  <h2>Chapter 4 &#8212; Understanding the Client &amp; Inherent Risk</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Before you can assess risk, you must understand the client. This drives identification of significant accounts and relevant assertions.</p>
  <h3>6 Areas of Client Understanding</h3>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Industry, regulatory, and other external factors</div><div class="desc">Industry-specific risks, regulatory requirements, competitive environment</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Nature of the company and related parties</div><div class="desc">Business model, organizational structure, related-party transactions</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Effect of client's IT / computerized processing</div><div class="desc">IT systems can introduce or mitigate risks; must understand the system</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Accounting principles and related disclosures</div><div class="desc">Which GAAP choices has management made? Why? Any unusual choices?</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Company objectives, strategies, and business risks</div><div class="desc">Strategic risks that could lead to misstatement</div></div></div>
  <div class="flow-step"><div class="step-num">6</div><div class="step-body"><div class="title">Company performance measures</div><div class="desc">KPIs, incentive structures, how management evaluates its own performance</div></div></div>
  <h3>Preliminary Analytical Procedures</h3>
  <div class="callout">Analytical procedures are REQUIRED in the planning phase and at the final review. OPTIONAL as substantive evidence. Used in planning to: identify potential problem areas, provide a standard starting point, and familiarize the auditor with the client's business.</div>
  <h3>Brainstorming (Audit Team Discussion)</h3>
  <div class="card"><strong>REQUIRED procedure &#8212; objectives:</strong><ul style="margin-top:6px;padding-left:1.1rem;"><li style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin-bottom:3px;">Gain understanding of previous experiences with the client</li><li style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin-bottom:3px;">Discuss how fraud might be perpetrated and concealed</li><li style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin-bottom:3px;">Identify which procedures might detect fraud</li><li style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin-bottom:3px;">Set the proper tone for the engagement</li><li style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);">Must be <strong style="color:var(--text);">ongoing throughout the engagement</strong> &#8212; not a one-time event</li></ul></div>
  <h3>Inquiries of Company Leadership</h3>
  <div class="grid3">
    <div class="card"><strong>Audit Committee</strong><p>Susceptibility to fraud, accounting principle selection, monitoring of fraud risks</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Management</strong><p>Selection of accounting principles, estimates, business risks</p></div>
    <div class="card"><strong>Internal Auditors</strong><p>Their findings, areas of concern, fraud risk assessment</p></div>
  </div>
  <h3>Significant Accounts and Relevant Assertions (AS 2110.59e)</h3>
  <div class="callout"><strong>Two key definitions:</strong><br>An account or disclosure is <strong>significant</strong> if there is a reasonable possibility it could contain a material misstatement &#8212; based on INHERENT RISK, WITHOUT regard to controls.<br><br>An assertion is <strong>relevant</strong> if there is a reasonable possibility it could contain a material misstatement &#8212; also based on inherent risk, without regard to controls.</div>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--text2);margin-top:8px;">Factors that increase inherent risk: fair value estimates requiring subjective judgment, complex transactions, management incentives to misstate, related-party transactions, history of prior misstatements.</p>
</div>
</main>
</div>

